title: After a couple of hours, geth loses his shit and starts screaming BAD BLOCK at everything

body: Those are canonical blocks, e.g. https://etherscan.io/block/4814596 . I've no idea why it would behave like this, but my _guess_ would be that there's a data corruption. If this happens repeatedly, I'd guess that your hard drive has faults. IIRC, the same thing has been reported before (by @Arachnid ?), and it stopped happening when he replaced his drive.

I'm using an SSD and just finished the --fast sync less then two days ago. 

The system logs do not indicate any I/O errors happening and the system is using DDR4 ECC memory so memory corruption is unlikely. Chances of SSD's randomly corrupting data (in just two days) is unlikely as well.

Disabling the single thread mining and not specifying the cache does not resolve it either.

Should I just try to totally start over again with a fresh --fast sync?

I'm actually suspecting a issue with the open file limit being reached, I'm currently compiling with the hard coded soft limit of 2048 increased to 65536.

Will report back

With the increase of the open file limit to 65536 the server has been running for over 5 hours so far without any issues. Maybe it would be advisable to include a command line option to manually increase the open file limit instead of hardcoding it?
It could also be an interesting experiment to make leveldb use less and larger files (exponentially larger the deeper the data gets).
This issue has been automatically marked as stale because it has not had recent activity. It will be closed if no further activity occurs. Thank you for your contributions.
